                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>S. MORAIS&#44;<lb/>
                546 NORTH FIFTH ST.&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia&#44; December 25th 1888<lb/></p>
            <p>Moses A. Dropsie Esq<lb/>
                Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Conceding that according to the Rabbinical<lb/> axiom &#34;a part of the year is reckoned a year&#44;&#34; as for<lb/> instance&#58; A <del>sovereign mounting the Nirine</del> King chosen in Adar&#44;<lb/> when Nisan began&#44; would have been considered as having<lb/> entered into the second year of his reign&#59; admitting again&#44;<lb/> that the Jewish sages have taught &#34;a part of the day is taken<lb/> as the whole&#44;&#34; for example&#44; some acts denoting mourning during<lb/> the first hour of the seventh day&#44; <del>counts for the entire day&#44; and</del> absolves from any<lb/> <del>no</del> further mourning needs be observed the rest of the day&#44; still I do not find<lb/> that the maxims have a universal application.  Certainly<lb/> not in cases of <hi rend="underline">Meum</hi> and <hi rend="underline">Tuum</hi>.  Thus a person<lb/> <del>renting</del> letting a house <del>or a field</del> by the year dares not <del>remove</del> evict the tenant after<lb/> the first day or week of the twelfth month has arrived.<lb/>  So I learn from <del>J</del> Talmudical authorities.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>But I will search farther&#44; and communicate the re&#45;<lb/>sult of my studies.<lb/></p>
            <p>Permit me to call your attention to the circumstance<lb/> that Monsieur Dupin Ainee&#45;&#45;an eminent French<lb/> <sic>loyer</sic>&#45;&#45;arguing against Monsieur J. Salvador&#44; though&#44;<lb/> <del>of course&#44; to the</del> greatly prejudiced against the Hebrew contemporaries<lb/> of Jesus&#44; agrees with you that the Romans took always<lb/> good care not to part with the regret of passing judgment<lb/> on what involved the penalty of death&#44; however indifferent<lb/> they may have been in other respects.  He quotes<lb/> Tacitus&#33;  Apend Benianos&#44; <hi rend="underline">jus valet gladii&#44; caetera trans</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">nuthiatur</hi>.<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours truly<lb/>
                S. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>P. S.  Having inquired further into the subject&#44; I have become convinced that to<lb/> apply indiscriminately the maxim of the Talmudist Abba Shaul&#44; &#34;a portion of the day is like the whole&#34;<lb/> <del>indiscriminately</del> would be to err&#59; for in the very instance of the observance of mourn&#45;<lb/>ing&#44; it is said that a person having cost a relative three days before a Biblical holiday&#44; though exo&#45;<lb/>riated from keeping the rest of the week&#44; is not allowed to bathe till the evening of the<lb/> third day&#44; and we do not consider in that case &#34;a portion of the day is like the whole&#34;<lb/> &#40;see Moed Katan. 19. 2 &#38; Rashi in Loed&#41; SM<lb/></p>
